on of boyhood that became the ideal was one that stressed selflessness, togetherness, honesty, fearlessness, frank determination, and emotional toughness. It was thought that investing boys with this version of masculinity was essential if they were to grow into the kind of citizens capable of governing, protecting, and defending the nation, and, of course, maintaining and regulating the social order.Drawing on a wide variety of sources, Ontario Boys demonstrates that, although girls were expected and encouraged to internalize a “special kind” of citizenship, as caregivers and educators of children and nurturers of men, the gendered content and language employed indicated that active public citizenship and democracy was intended for boys. An “appropriate” boyhood in the postwar period became, if nothing else, a metaphor for the survival of the nation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBoyszOntarioxHistoriography. 0aBoyszOntarioxHistoryy20th century. 0aMasculinityxSocial aspectszOntarioxHistoryy20th century. 4aCultural Studies. 4aHistory: Canadian History. 4aSocial Science: Child Studies. 4aSocial Science: Gender Studies. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aBoyhood.  aBoys.  aGender.  aMasculinity.  aPostwar Ontario.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311127407208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014z978311127709740uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978155458901240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781554589012423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781554589012/original  a978-3-11-127407-2  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-127709-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles